    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-07-07T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-07-07T03:00:00-05:00" n="529"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d529">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">394.1153 Smith Company, Werner G./21:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-07-07T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >July 7, 1938—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 7—11:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>961. Tokyo’s 443, July 6, 6 p.m.<note n="8" xml:id="d529fn8">See last paragraph
                        of telegram No. 956, July 7, 9 a.m., from the Consul General at Shanghai,
                            <ref target="#pg_394">p. 394</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>The Japanese authorities both at Nanking and Shanghai have repeatedly been
                        assured that the wood oil is the property of the Werner Gr. Smith Company,
                        an American concern at Hankow. The Consulate General endeavored some weeks
                        ago without success to obtain from Hankow documentary proof of ownership to
                        support this statement. The Japanese authorities, although not entirely
                        satisfied, have now tacitly recognized American ownership.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>The Japanese naval authorities’ contention that the Yangtze is not yet
                        open to commercial traffic is only partially true because Japanese vessels
                        pass freely up and down the Yangtze between Shanghai and Nanking and have
                        accepted freight.</item>
                </list>
                <p>Repeated to Hankow and Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
